=========================================
C++ std::forward_list (Singly Linked List)
INTERVIEW NOTES (CLEAN & FINAL)
=========================================

1. What is forward_list?
------------------------
std::forward_list is a singly linked list in STL.

Each node contains:
[data | next]

Example:
10 -> 20 -> 30 -> NULL

- Stores only forward link
- Memory efficient compared to std::list

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation (IMPORTANT)
--------------------------------------
- Implemented as singly linked list
- Each node has:
  1. data
  2. pointer to next node only

Unlike std::list:
- NO prev pointer

-----------------------------------------

3. Why use forward_list?
------------------------
✔ Lower memory usage than list
✔ Fast insertion/deletion after a node
✔ Useful when backward traversal not needed

-----------------------------------------

4. Difference: list vs forward_list ****************
------------------------------------

list (doubly linked list):
- prev + next pointers
- bidirectional traversal
- more memory

forward_list (singly linked list):
- only next pointer
- forward traversal only
- less memory

-----------------------------------------

5. Why no push_back()?
-----------------------
- No tail pointer tracking
- Must traverse entire list to reach end

Cost:
O(n)

👉 So STL does NOT provide push_back()

-----------------------------------------

6. Why insert_after() instead of insert()?
------------------------------------------
Because each node knows ONLY next node.

Example:
10 -> 20 -> 30

Insert after 10:
insert_after(it, 15)

Result:
10 -> 15 -> 20 -> 30

-----------------------------------------

7. Complexity (VERY IMPORTANT)
------------------------------
push_front()     -> O(1)
pop_front()      -> O(1)
insert_after()   -> O(1)
erase_after()    -> O(1)
access/search    -> O(n)
size()           -> O(n) or O(1) depending on implementation

-----------------------------------------

8. Random Access
-----------------
❌ Not supported

Example:
fl[5] // ERROR

Reason:
- Nodes are not contiguous
- Must traverse sequentially

-----------------------------------------

9. Iterator Behavior
---------------------
✔ Iterators are forward-only
✔ No backward traversal

-----------------------------------------

10. When to use forward_list?
-----------------------------
Use when:
✔ Memory is critical
✔ Only forward traversal needed
✔ Frequent insert/delete after known node

Avoid when:
✗ Need backward traversal
✗ Need random access
✗ Need frequent tail operations

-----------------------------------------

11. Common Functions
--------------------
push_front()
pop_front()

front()

insert_after()
erase_after()

begin()
end()

empty()
clear()

remove()
sort()
reverse()
unique()

-----------------------------------------

12. Key Functions Explained
---------------------------

insert_after(it, value)
- Inserts after given iterator
- O(1)

erase_after(it)
- Deletes next node
- O(1)

remove(x)
- Removes all occurrences of x

sort()
- Sorts list (custom implementation)

unique()
- Removes consecutive duplicates

reverse()
- Reverses list

-----------------------------------------

13. Memory Advantage
---------------------
Each node stores:
[data + next]

vs list:
[data + prev + next]

👉 forward_list uses less memory per node

-----------------------------------------

14. One-line Interview Answer
-----------------------------
std::forward_list is a singly linked list that supports O(1) insertion and deletion after a known position, 
uses less memory than std::list, but allows only forward traversal and no random access.

-----------------------------------------

15. QUICK REVISION
------------------
1. Singly linked list
2. Only next pointer
3. No random access
4. No push_back()
5. insert_after O(1)
6. erase_after O(1)
7. Less memory than list
8. Forward traversal only
9. No backward iteration
10. Used for memory-efficient linked operations

